<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Loeffel_03.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Loef=
fel_03.JPG/250px-Loeffel_03.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"235" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2563" data-file-height=
=3D"2409"></a><figcaption>left-to-right: <div class=3D"plainlist"><ul><li><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serving_spoon" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Serving spoon">Serving spoon</a></li><li>Tablespoon (tbsp.)</li>=
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dessert_spoon" title=3D"Desser=
t spoon">Dessert spoon</a> (dsp.)</li><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Teaspoon" title=3D"Teaspoon">Teaspoon</a> (tsp.)</li></ul></div></f=
igcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>tablespoon</b> (tbsp., Tbsp., Tb., or T.) is a large <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spoon" title=3D"Spoon">spoon</a>. In many Englis=
h-speaking regions, the term now refers to a large spoon used for serving.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In some regions, it is the large=
st type of spoon used for eating.
</p><p>By extension, the term is also used as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Cooking_measures" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cooking meas=
ures">cooking measure</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volum=
e" title=3D"Volume">volume</a>. In this capacity, it is most commonly abbre=
viated <i>tbsp.</i> or <i>Tbsp.</i> and occasionally referred to as a <b>ta=
blespoonful</b> to distinguish it from the utensil. The unit of measurement=
 varies by region: a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States=
_customary_units" title=3D"United States customary units">United States liq=
uid</a> tablespoon is approximately 14.8&nbsp;mL, exactly <span class=3D"fr=
ac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span=
> US fluid ounce; about 0.52 imperial fluid ounce. A British tablespoon is =
approximately 14.2&nbsp;mL, exactly <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-sty=
le" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span =
class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> imperial=
 fluid ounce; about 0.48 US fluid ounce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_note-2"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>An international metric tablespoon is exactly 15&nbsp;mL, about 0.53=
 imperial fluid ounce or 0.51 US fluid ounce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_not=
e-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> An Australian metric tablespoon is 20&nbsp;mL, about 0.7 im=
perial fluid ounce or 0.68 US fluid ounce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_note-4">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> The capacity of the utensil, as opposed to the measurement, is d=
efined by neither law nor custom but only by preferences, and may or may no=
t significantly approximate the measurement.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Dining">Dining</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTablespoon&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Dining"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Before about 1700, it was customary for Europeans to bring their own spo=
ons to the table.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2024)">citation ne=
eded</span></a></i>]</sup> Spoons were carried as personal property in much=
 the same way as people today carry wallets, key rings, etc. From about 170=
0 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Place_setting" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Place setting">place setting</a> became popular, and with=
 it the "table-spoon" (hyphenated), "table-fork" and "table-knife". Around =
the same time the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teaspoon" title=
=3D"Teaspoon">tea-spoon</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De=
ssert_spoon" title=3D"Dessert spoon">dessert-spoon</a> first appeared. The =
table-spoon was reserved for eating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Soup" title=3D"Soup">soup</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_note-5"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The 18th century witnessed a proliferation of different sorts of spoons, i=
ncluding the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mustard_spoon" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mustard spoon">mustard-spoon</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_spoon" title=3D"Salt spoon">salt-spoon</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coffee_spoon" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Coffee spoon">coffee-spoon</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Soup_spoon" title=3D"Soup spoon">soup-spoon</a>.
</p><p>In the late 19th century UK, the dessert-spoon and soup-spoon began =
to displace the table-spoon as the primary implement for eating from a bowl=
, at which point the name "table-spoon" took on a secondary meaning as a mu=
ch larger <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serving_spoon" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Serving spoon">serving spoon</a>.<sup class=3D"noprin=
t Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikip=
edia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliabl=
e sources. (April 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> In 1928, whe=
n the first edition of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_=
English_Dictionary" title=3D"Oxford English Dictionary">Oxford English Dict=
ionary</a> was published, "tablespoon", which by then was no longer hyphena=
ted, still had two definitions in the UK: the original definition (eating s=
poon) and the new definition (serving spoon).
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victorian_era" title=3D"Vic=
torian era">Victorian</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edwa=
rdian_era" title=3D"Edwardian era">Edwardian era</a> tablespoons used in th=
e UK are often 25&nbsp;mL, about 0.88 imperial fluid ounce or 0.85 US fluid=
 ounce, or sometimes larger.  They are used only for preparing and serving =
food, not as part of a place-setting. Common tablespoons intended for use a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cutlery" title=3D"Cutlery">cutle=
ry</a>, called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dessert_spoon" titl=
e=3D"Dessert spoon">dessert spoons</a> in the UK, where a tablespoon is alw=
ays a serving spoon, usually hold 7=E2=80=9314&nbsp;mL, about 0.25=E2=80=93=
0.49 imperial fluid ounce or 0.24=E2=80=930.47 US fluid ounce,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabl=
espoon#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> considerably less than some tablespoons used=
 for serving.
</p>
