,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-us_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_note-us-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> about 4.22 British =
imperial fluid drachms (0.53 British imperial fluid ounce) or 4.06 US custo=
mary fluid drams, 0.51 US customary fluid ounce.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Dry_measure">Dry measure</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTablespoon&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Dry measure"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dry_measure" title=3D"Dry measur=
e">Dry measure</a></div>
<p>For dry ingredients, if a recipe calls for a <i>level tablespoon</i>, th=
e usual meaning without further qualification, is measured by filling the s=
poon and scraping it level. In contrast, a <i>heaped</i>, <i>heaping</i>, o=
r <i>rounded</i> spoonful is not leveled off, and includes a heap above the=
 spoon. The exact volume of a heaped tablespoon depends somewhat on the sha=
pe and curvature of the measuring spoon being used and largely upon the phy=
sical properties of the substance being measured, and so is not a precise u=
nit of measurement. If neither a rounded nor a level tablespoon is specifie=
d, a level tablespoon is used, just as a cup of flour is a level cup unless=
 otherwise specified.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Apothecary_measure">Apothec=
ary measure</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Tablespoon&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Apoth=
ecary measure"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>In the 18th century, the table-spoon became an unofficial unit of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apothecaries%27_system" title=3D"Apo=
thecaries' system">apothecaries' system</a> of measures, equal to 4&nbsp;dr=
ams (<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSty=
les:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span =
class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2=
</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz, 14.8&nbsp;&nbsp;mL). It was=
 more commonly known by the Latin name <i>cochleare majus</i> (abbreviated =
<i>cochl. maj.</i>) or, in apothecaries' notation, <i>f=E2=84=A5ss</i> or <=
i>f=E2=84=A5=C3=9F</i> (<b>f</b>luid =E2=84=A5, i.e. ounce, <b>s</b>emi<b>s=
</b>, one-half).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-encyclopedia1884_14-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_note-encyclope=
dia1884-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-RitterJohnstone1910_15-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon#cite_not=
e-RitterJohnstone1910-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hazell's_annual_16=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablespoon=
#cite_note-Hazell's_annual-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
